			<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; " >
												<P>I have played EQ since it first came out, and my bard is and was my main. I have left her several times over the years to give my wrist a break, something NO OTHER class has to do. Yet I always come back. I have hated macros since I first heard about them but finally I have reached a point where it is use macros and keep playing my beloved bard or stop playing. Real life injury to play a game just doesn't make sense!</P>
<P>Last week I&nbsp;purchased the Nostromo N52. While I love the fact that I can now talk to others while playing it is definately not the end all and be all of a bard fix. Yes, I can program it to twist a sequence of songs for me, which really helps reduce the strain on my wrist, but once that macro had begun there is no flexibility to it. I find that I use it more for the times when I am really hurting, and twist using their more ergonomic pad with a single click /stopsong /cast 1 -8 (which incidently is alot more convenient on the game pad than on a keyboard!)</P>
<P>I never thought I would say it but macros make sense. The macro isn't evil, in and of itself. In fact, it is becoming rather precious to me! (gollum.. gollum)... yess.. my prexcioussss... we wants it!</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV></DIV>
																		
										</td></tr>
