			<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; " >
												Solution: someone make a macro program and bundle it with a cheap gamepad. In fact, make the software work with any standard gamepad on the market. Taking it a step further, it might work with keyboard shortcuts if you don't happen to have a gamepad connected.<br><br>Would it be allowed? I don't know and I doubt Sony will elaborate further, because if they set a clear rule they'll be bound by it themselves. They don't want to allow software that can be used for unattended macroing, and they don't want to tell people that they can't use a simple autofire macro or similar on a gamepad. It doesn't help us bards, but it leaves them free to enforce it selectively and ban whoever they want while not antagonising those using more benign simple macroing like that allowed by the Belkin pad. On the other hand, would it be better if people can use AFK exping macros as long as they're paying attention to the screen often enough to fake it being attended?<br><br>So use your common sense, don't use whatever macroing capability you have from gamepads or whatnot in stupid ways and you won't get in any trouble. Don't expect Sony to condone any macroing at all though, because that's a can of worm they want to stay away from.
																		
										</td></tr>
